01:27:31,813 --> 01:27:33,047
We don't have any money,

1548
01:27:33,081 --> 01:27:35,516
we don't have any backers to pay for all this.

1549
01:27:35,550 --> 01:27:38,419
[man] What? Food on the Earth is so freaking good.

1550
01:27:38,820 --> 01:27:41,990
Besides, they say you shouldn't fight on an empty stomach.

1551
01:27:43,458 --> 01:27:47,395
Fight, huh? Yeah, we can't afford to do that either.

1552
01:27:47,428 --> 01:27:51,299
[man] Then I'll look forward to when we can. There you go lady.

1553
01:27:53,701 --> 01:27:56,070
Next time I'll come here to feast on the Earth itself.

1554
01:27:57,038 --> 01:27:58,506
[man 2] Those are some tall words

1555
01:27:58,539 --> 01:28:00,441
you're spoutin' there, big britches.

1556
01:28:00,475 --> 01:28:02,677
[man] Gotta dream big, money or no money.

1557
01:28:02,710 --> 01:28:04,979
[man 2 chuckles] Don't be a nincompoop.

1558
01:28:06,748 --> 01:28:10,551
Oh! Good job noticing us! [laughs]

1559
01:28:11,586 --> 01:28:16,591
- [gun firing] - [ObaZ screams]

1560
01:28:18,426 --> 01:28:20,728
[soft music]

1561
01:28:21,796 --> 01:28:23,097
[paper rustling]

1562
01:28:23,831 --> 01:28:25,566
[Sakamoto] We haven't talked in a while.

1563
01:28:25,600 --> 01:28:27,568
Hope this letter finds you well.

1564
01:28:27,602 --> 01:28:30,338
How have you been, Peen-toki?

1565
01:28:31,606 --> 01:28:34,676
Yeah, I've been flying across the universe as always.

1566
01:28:34,709 --> 01:28:38,112
You know, space is pretty bitchin', my friend.

1567
01:28:38,146 --> 01:28:41,883
You should join me on a trip sometime, Vagin-toki.

1568
01:28:42,984 --> 01:28:44,886
Anyway, the reason I'm writing you

1569
01:28:45,153 --> 01:28:46,721
is because I have something

1570
01:28:46,754 --> 01:28:48,122
important I'd like to say.

1571
01:28:49,857 --> 01:28:52,727
That day, when I promised a brave and heroic

1572
01:28:52,760 --> 01:28:55,863
rescue of you and everyone else, well,

1573
01:28:55,897 --> 01:28:57,632
once I saw the Terminal crumble down,

1574
01:28:57,665 --> 01:29:01,803
I was thinking, \"They dead, lololol.\" [chuckles]

1575
01:29:01,836 --> 01:29:04,138
[soft music]

1576
01:29:07,942 --> 01:29:09,177
I don't mean this to sound as

1577
01:29:09,210 --> 01:29:11,813
some sort of consolation or anything,

1578
01:29:11,846 --> 01:29:14,749
Because I truly believe, deep in my heart of hearts

1579
01:29:14,782 --> 01:29:18,119
that he saved you back then, so please,

1580
01:29:18,152 --> 01:29:20,822
you don't need to beat yourself up over it.

1581
01:29:20,855 --> 01:29:23,725
Your teacher's soul lives on everywhere on Earth,

1582
01:29:23,758 --> 01:29:27,161
and he continues to watch over you, I'm sure of that.

1583
01:29:27,195 --> 01:29:29,063
And I know you can feel it too.

1584
01:29:30,498 --> 01:29:34,836
To my beloved friend, Peen-vaginto-fuk-u.

1585
01:29:34,869 --> 01:29:38,573
PS, I heard something when I ran into Zura the other day.

1586
01:29:39,073 --> 01:29:41,075
It would seem the remnants of the Kiheitai

1587
01:29:41,109 --> 01:29:42,910
are making some curious moves.

1588
01:29:44,846 --> 01:29:45,947
[Katsura] The gates?

1589
01:29:46,214 --> 01:29:47,782
Indeed.

1590
01:29:47,815 --> 01:29:49,417
[Katsura] Who do you think you're mimicking?

1591
01:29:49,817 --> 01:29:52,553
She probably couldn't stand the fact

1592
01:29:52,587 --> 01:29:54,655
that she was so powerless.

1593
01:29:54,689 --> 01:29:56,624
[soft music]

1594
01:29:56,657 --> 01:29:58,092
But she was thankful

1595
01:29:58,760 --> 01:30:01,062
that after he was a prisoner for so long,

1596
01:30:01,095 --> 01:30:03,431
she could see him smile, once again.

1597
01:30:03,631 --> 01:30:05,700
[music continues]

1598
01:30:06,801 --> 01:30:10,772
And she says that now it's her turn.

1599
01:30:13,107 --> 01:30:14,876
[Katsura] Well, there is no chance of him

1600
01:30:14,909 --> 01:30:16,978
coming back to life like Utsuro did.

1601
01:30:18,045 --> 01:30:19,814
That was a miracle which only occurred

1602
01:30:19,847 --> 01:30:21,682
because he was born from Altana.

1603
01:30:23,251 --> 01:30:26,587
[groans] That's how it is and it's fine.

1604
01:30:26,988 --> 01:30:30,091
This is simply how we, the Kiheitai,

1605
01:30:30,124 --> 01:30:31,959
atone for the sins we've committed.

1606
01:30:34,095 --> 01:30:38,833
Takechi, you too. You're also abandoning me.

1607
01:30:41,602 --> 01:30:44,238
[paper rustling]

1608
01:30:50,711 --> 01:30:52,947
[Sakamoto] In the end, here's what I believe.

1609
01:30:52,980 --> 01:30:57,118
Miracles are not real. Sorry, they're just not.

1610
01:30:57,151 --> 01:30:59,153
[panting]

1611
01:31:00,154 --> 01:31:02,156
[soft music]

1612
01:31:02,957 --> 01:31:05,493
[indistinct chattering]

1613
01:31:14,268 --> 01:31:16,737
Whenever a teacher protects their student...

1614
01:31:17,305 --> 01:31:19,140
[baby cooing]

1615
01:31:21,175 --> 01:31:22,844
[Sakamoto] ...you cannot call that a miracle.

1616
01:31:23,311 --> 01:31:26,080
[music continues]

1617
01:31:26,914 --> 01:31:29,016
- [water trickling] - [coos]

1618
01:31:29,050 --> 01:31:32,019
[Sakamoto] Because that is just what they do.

1619
01:31:32,053 --> 01:31:34,155
[crying]

1620
01:31:36,791 --> 01:31:39,026
[footsteps approaching]

1621
01:31:40,061 --> 01:31:41,929
Oh, look who's here?

1622
01:31:44,632 --> 01:31:46,901
It's been a while since we came to see Father together.

1623
01:31:47,935 --> 01:31:50,838
- Do you have any news for him? - I don't.

1624
01:31:51,305 --> 01:31:54,942
When Father died, he lamented the state of Edo's skies...

1625
01:31:54,976 --> 01:31:58,679
[spaceship engine revving]

1626
01:31:59,814 --> 01:32:01,816
[birds chirping]

1627
01:32:02,350 --> 01:32:04,619
...but whenever I look upon them now,

1628
01:32:04,652 --> 01:32:06,921
these same old skies look a bit different.

1629
01:32:07,188 --> 01:32:10,057
[soft music]

1630
01:32:14,829 --> 01:32:17,965
[Shinpachi] After all, there is one thing we do know,

1631
01:32:18,933 --> 01:32:23,037
that the people we care about, they live under these skies.

1632
01:32:23,971 --> 01:32:26,240
[electricity whooshing]

1633
01:32:29,911 --> 01:32:32,914
Sure, the skies might get cloudy at times,

1634
01:32:33,381 --> 01:32:36,117
but in our hearts, beneath our skies

1635
01:32:37,118 --> 01:32:39,687
live all the people I love so much.

1636
01:32:42,123 --> 01:32:44,825
[music continues]

1637
01:32:54,669 --> 01:32:57,838
[Shinpachi] So, Tama, even if you find yourself

1638
01:32:58,072 --> 01:33:02,977
beneath unfamiliar skies, please don't cry.

1639
01:33:04,111 --> 01:33:06,847
We will always remain in your heart with you.

1640
01:33:07,748 --> 01:33:11,152
And if you'll believe in that, then I'm certain,

1641
01:33:12,853 --> 01:33:16,757
we will come to you and wipe your tears away.

1642
01:33:20,861 --> 01:33:23,764
[soft music]

1643
01:33:36,777 --> 01:33:37,778
Let's keep going.

1644
01:33:39,914 --> 01:33:41,415
[siren wailing]

1645
01:33:41,449 --> 01:33:43,718
[Hasegawa] After that, these lovely ladies

1646
01:33:43,751 --> 01:33:46,787
went on to live as citizens of the modern age.

1647
01:33:47,321 --> 01:33:52,293
The world was entering a golden age of techno technology.

1648
01:33:52,326 --> 01:33:54,028
Machines, and not people,

1649
01:33:54,061 --> 01:33:56,831
were to be the new leaders of civilization.

1650
01:33:56,864 --> 01:33:59,266
And these girls, well, they were robots,

1651
01:33:59,300 --> 01:34:00,801
so they lived happy lives.

1652
01:34:01,135 --> 01:34:05,706
Turns out it was the humans who ended up unemployed.

1653
01:34:05,740 --> 01:34:07,775
Yeah, that's right, every last one of them.

1654
01:34:07,808 --> 01:34:09,143
You see, if nobody has a job,

1655
01:34:09,176 --> 01:34:12,013
they can't ridicule anybody else for being unemployed.

1656
01:34:12,046 --> 01:34:15,182
The jobless become one and everyone's happy. You dig?

1657
01:34:15,950 --> 01:34:16,951
[chuckles]

1658
01:34:17,918 --> 01:34:20,388
Every single person can be happy. [laughs]

1659
01:34:20,421 --> 01:34:24,225
That's Mister Hasegawa. Why is he here in the future?

1660
01:34:25,026 --> 01:34:26,227
[electricity crackling]

1661
01:34:26,794 --> 01:34:28,195
Tamako, let me tell you how

1662
01:34:28,229 --> 01:34:30,064
this story really ends, all right?

1663
01:34:30,097 --> 01:34:33,234
You see, Edo's gonna turn into a... [burps]

1664
01:34:33,467 --> 01:34:36,070
Um, hey Number Zero, the data I gave you

1665
01:34:36,103 --> 01:34:38,706
might have contained some massive errors!

1666
01:34:39,106 --> 01:34:40,808
What kind of massive errors?

1667
01:34:43,477 --> 01:34:46,847
[all] You're trying to bullshit the narration too?

1668
01:34:48,115 --> 01:34:49,884
[Shinpachi] What in the holy hell did you tell Tamako?

1669
01:34:49,917 --> 01:34:51,852
[Hasegawa] I was just saying how hard it was to find work

1670
01:34:51,886 --> 01:34:52,953
after I quit being the hero.

1671
01:34:54,188 --> 01:34:55,256
I mean, turns out that people like heroes, right? [groans]

1672
01:34:56,390 --> 01:34:59,160
My sincere apologies, it seems this world we perceived

1673
01:34:59,193 --> 01:35:00,394
has encountered a few glitches,

1674
01:35:00,428 --> 01:35:03,998
with the inclusion of Hasegawa's data, it has some problems.

1675
01:35:04,031 --> 01:35:05,433
[electricity whooshing]

1676
01:35:05,466 --> 01:35:07,334
[upbeat music]

1677
01:35:07,368 --> 01:35:09,970
The real world must be something else.

1678
01:35:10,004 --> 01:35:12,740
[music continues]

1679
01:35:15,242 --> 01:35:16,977
Hey, and good morning to you.

1680
01:35:19,180 --> 01:35:21,415
You look like you're half-asleep or something.

1681
01:35:22,383 --> 01:35:24,485
Whatever, we've got some extremely

1682
01:35:24,518 --> 01:35:26,787
urgent work to take care of.

1683
01:35:26,821 --> 01:35:28,422
We'll have to catch up with you later.

1684
01:35:29,023 --> 01:35:30,224
[Shinpachi] Huh? Wait, Gin!

1685
01:35:32,293 --> 01:35:33,294
Oh, and,

1686
01:35:35,029 --> 01:35:37,031
you don't need us to wipe those tears away, right?

1687
01:35:38,099 --> 01:35:40,801
Looks like the big guy upstairs feels better.

1688
01:35:40,835 --> 01:35:42,269
He stopped his crying, too.

1689
01:35:43,137 --> 01:35:45,272
The skies above are all clear.

1690
01:35:49,243 --> 01:35:50,878
Let's go.

1691
01:35:50,911 --> 01:35:52,546
[music continues]

1692
01:35:52,580 --> 01:35:53,781
[Sadaharu barks]

1693
01:35:56,183 --> 01:35:58,185
[Kagura] Hey, Gin, where are we going?

1694
01:35:58,953 --> 01:36:01,122
What--what is this work we have to do?

1695
01:36:01,155 --> 01:36:02,356
[Gintoki] Oh yeah. What was that?

1696
01:36:02,389 --> 01:36:05,292
[Shinpachi] You forgot? You said it was extremely urgent!

1697
01:36:05,326 --> 01:36:06,427
[Gintoki] You mean, you don't remember?

1698
01:36:06,460 --> 01:36:07,461
[Shinpachi] What? No!

1699
01:36:08,629 --> 01:36:09,463
[Gintoki] Well, hey, it doesn't matter what, right?

1700
01:36:12,066 --> 01:36:13,467
- [Kagura laughs] - [Gintoki] After all,

1701
01:36:15,069 --> 01:36:16,570
we're the Odd Jobs!

1702
01:36:16,604 --> 01:36:19,273
[music continues]

1703
01:36:33,921 --> 01:36:39,093
[upbeat music]

1704
01:37:50,264 --> 01:37:52,299
[music continues]

1705
01:38:26,500 --> 01:38:29,136
[music continues]

1706
01:39:25,626 --> 01:39:29,430
[music continues]

1707
01:40:14,441 --> 01:40:17,077
[Ginpachi-Sensei] Attention Class 3-Z.

1708
01:40:17,111 --> 01:40:19,580
[class] Teach us, Ginpachi-Sensei.

1709
01:40:20,547 --> 01:40:23,250
[Shinpachi] Stand, bow, take your seats.

1710
01:40:23,484 --> 01:40:26,086
Listen up, everyone, the manga and movie

1711
01:40:26,120 --> 01:40:27,354
have reached the final chapter.

1712
01:40:27,388 --> 01:40:29,289
So you guys, who have repeated this class,

1713
01:40:29,323 --> 01:40:31,558
year after year, finally get to graduate too.

1714
01:40:31,592 --> 01:40:34,328
Now meet transfer student, Hideaki Sorachi.

1715
01:40:34,628 --> 01:40:35,629
He says you can ask him

1716
01:40:36,663 --> 01:40:37,831
anything you want right now and he'll answer.

1717
01:40:37,865 --> 01:40:39,066
Question Sensei!

1718
01:40:40,167 --> 01:40:41,001
How are we supposed to communicate with a gorilla?

1719
01:40:41,035 --> 01:40:42,002
[Ginpachi-Sensei] What's he saying?

1720
01:40:42,036 --> 01:40:44,772
- All I hear is \"Unga-bunga.\" - Unga-bunga.

1721
01:40:44,805 --> 01:40:47,574
Sensei, an establishment containing multiple gorillas

1722
01:40:47,608 --> 01:40:50,210
would be a zoo, and not a school, may I go home now?

1723
01:40:50,477 --> 01:40:51,678
[Ginpachi-Sensei] Kondo, Sorachi, and Otae,

1724
01:40:51,712 --> 01:40:52,846
you may go home to your cages.

1725
01:40:52,880 --> 01:40:55,349
[groaning] Excuse me.

1726
01:40:55,582 --> 01:40:58,218
I can interpret the unga-bunga if you'd like, Sensei.

1727
01:40:58,252 --> 01:40:59,720
[Ginpachi-Sensei] You're the Sensei, Shoyo.

1728
01:40:59,753 --> 01:41:02,189
As someone who's been repeating all eternity,

1729
01:41:02,222 --> 01:41:03,724
I can understand every language.

1730
01:41:03,757 --> 01:41:05,859
[Ginpachi-Sensei] A guy who repeats forever is a crazy person, you know.

1731
01:41:06,427 --> 01:41:08,662
- This is the question Kondo has. - [ominous music]

1732
01:41:08,695 --> 01:41:11,432
Getting kicked off of a jump, two final chapter scams,

1733
01:41:11,465 --> 01:41:14,468
and series of multiple delays, why did all that happen?

1734
01:41:14,501 --> 01:41:15,803
[Kondo] That is a dangerous question!

1735
01:41:15,836 --> 01:41:17,504
He really is crazy, Sensei!

1736
01:41:17,538 --> 01:41:19,239
- [grunting] - Uh-huh.

1737
01:41:19,273 --> 01:41:20,707
Oh, I see. Is that what happened?

1738
01:41:20,741 --> 01:41:22,709
[Kondo] Sensei! You didn't even need an interpreter!

1739
01:41:22,743 --> 01:41:24,478
It's a rather delicate matter,

1740
01:41:24,511 --> 01:41:25,813
so we'll have to banana-coat it.

1741
01:41:25,846 --> 01:41:27,581
[Otae] Could you sugarcoat it instead?

1742
01:41:27,614 --> 01:41:28,882
- [ominous music] - [Ginpachi-Sensei] It's like this.

1743
01:41:28,916 --> 01:41:30,751
[Kondo] The banana peel isn't working!

1744
01:41:30,784 --> 01:41:32,820
The Sekiro is there for all to see!

1745
01:41:32,853 --> 01:41:34,221
Okay, forget the banana.

1746
01:41:34,254 --> 01:41:35,722
Things got crazy after Isshin

1747
01:41:35,756 --> 01:41:37,357
tore his way out of Genichiro's back.

1748
01:41:37,391 --> 01:41:38,859
[Otae] Please, stop talking about Sekiro.

1749
01:41:38,892 --> 01:41:40,461
It'll just cause online drama.

1750
01:41:40,494 --> 01:41:41,662
Anybody else got a questions?

1751
01:41:41,695 --> 01:41:42,930
[Kondo] I'm too scared to ask!

1752
01:41:42,963 --> 01:41:44,164
I have a question.

1753
01:41:45,365 --> 01:41:47,334
We never got any details about Gintoki Sakata's origins.

1754
01:41:47,367 --> 01:41:48,368
So I would like to know.

1755
01:41:49,636 --> 01:41:50,437
There's a fan theory that says he's half-Amanto

1756
01:41:51,538 --> 01:41:52,473
because of the whole silver hair thing.

1757
01:41:52,506 --> 01:41:54,241
Does that mean Sacchan with her purple hair

1758
01:41:54,274 --> 01:41:55,909
is really half-Osakan hag?

1759
01:41:55,943 --> 01:41:59,213
So rude! How can anyone be half an Osakan hag?

1760
01:41:59,246 --> 01:42:01,648
Don't worry, Sarutobi. You are not an Osakan hag.

1761
01:42:01,682 --> 01:42:03,250
More of a Nagoyan hag.

1762
01:42:03,283 --> 01:42:04,451
I'm not a hag!

1763
01:42:04,485 --> 01:42:06,653
Does that mean silver -haired guy is--

1764
01:42:06,687 --> 01:42:08,622
Half-Sugamo-old-fart-geezer?

1765
01:42:08,655 --> 01:42:11,391
- Ooga-booga-booga. - I hate to say it, but you're all wrong.

1766
01:42:11,425 --> 01:42:13,660
Keep it between us, but there's a banana-coated

1767
01:42:13,694 --> 01:42:15,262
reason for the silver hair.

1768
01:42:15,295 --> 01:42:16,296
[ominous music]

1769
01:42:17,564 --> 01:42:18,699
[Kondo] Too blunt! The banana-coating is failing!

1770
01:42:19,633 --> 01:42:20,868
Are there any other questions out there?

1771
01:42:20,901 --> 01:42:22,936
[Kondo] That's enough, Sensei! We'll just dig our own graves!

1772
01:42:22,970 --> 01:42:26,273
Okay, then I shall turn everything hollow,

1773
01:42:26,306 --> 01:42:28,542
with this one perfect question to end them all.

1774
01:42:28,575 --> 01:42:31,411
[Ginpachi-Sensei] Shoyo's other persona, Hollow-Brain's here.

1775
01:42:31,445 --> 01:42:32,779
He's gonna say something stupid!

1776
01:42:32,813 --> 01:42:36,850
Sorachi, I have a question for you. Riddle me this.

1777
01:42:37,518 --> 01:42:39,386
Do you count bananas as snackies?

1778
01:42:39,419 --> 01:42:41,822
- [Kondo] That was Shoyo! - Stay out of this, Shoyo!

1779
01:42:41,855 --> 01:42:45,492
What I want to ask is, do you consider bananas as royalties?

1780
01:42:45,526 --> 01:42:47,528
No, no, bananas count as snackies.

1781
01:42:47,561 --> 01:42:49,296
[Ginpachi-Sensei] Looks like both of their questions are trash.

1782
01:42:49,329 --> 01:42:50,397
Banana is royalties!

1783
01:42:51,832 --> 01:42:53,967
[Ginpachi-Sensei] Somebody stop those two morons or that one moron.

1784
01:42:54,001 --> 01:42:55,235
Any other questions?

1785
01:42:56,170 --> 01:42:57,905
Sensei! What was that ObaZ stuff all about?

1786
01:42:57,938 --> 01:42:59,606
[Ginpachi-Sensei] You need to drop it already.

1787
01:42:59,640 --> 01:43:02,309
Sensei, I have a question about

1788
01:43:02,342 --> 01:43:03,710
something very important to me.

1789
01:43:03,744 --> 01:43:05,379
Am I alive? Or am I dead?

1790
01:43:05,412 --> 01:43:07,347
[Kondo] It's Takasugi! He's right.

1791
01:43:07,381 --> 01:43:09,616
His survival was kind of left up in the air, wasn't it?

1792
01:43:10,450 --> 01:43:12,286
